All four areas you described hit .NET 11 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and how to fix each:

---

**1. GZipStream empty payload (behavioral)**
In .NET 11, `GZipStream` now writes valid headers/footers even when no data is compressed. Your zero-length check will never trigger.

**Fix:** Check the uncompressed byte count instead of output stream length.

```csharp
// ❌ .NET 11: ms.Length is now > 0 even with no data
if (ms.Length == 0) { /* "no data" */ }

// ✅ Track whether you actually wrote anything
if (uncompressedByteCount == 0) { /* "no data" */ }
```

---

**2. TAR header checksum validation (behavioral)**
TAR-reading APIs now verify header checksums. Your hand-crafted/legacy TAR files with invalid checksums will **throw at runtime**.

**Fix:** Either fix the legacy tool to produce valid checksums, or wrap `TarReader.GetNextEntry()` in error handling:

```csharp
try {
    var entry = reader.GetNextEntry();
} catch (InvalidDataException) {
    // Handle corrupted/legacy TAR files
}
```

---

**3. ZipArchive.CreateAsync eager loading (behavioral)**
`ZipArchive.CreateAsync` now **eagerly** loads all entries into memory instead of lazy loading. For your large ZIP files, this means a memory spike on open.

**Fix:** Be aware of higher peak memory usage. For very large archives, consider streaming entry-by-entry or increasing memory budgets. If you relied on lazy loading to avoid reading unused entries, that optimization is gone.

---

**4. MemoryStream maximum capacity (behavioral)**
The maximum capacity and the exception behavior for exceeding it have changed. Code allocating near the old maximum may now get different exceptions or different limits.

**Fix:** Review any code that creates very large `MemoryStream` instances or catches specific exception types (e.g., `OutOfMemoryException` vs `IOException`) related to capacity limits. Test with your actual large allocation sizes.

---

**Summary:** All four are **runtime behavioral changes** — your code will still compile cleanly but behave differently. The TAR checksum change is the most disruptive (throws where it previously succeeded silently). Prioritize adding error handling there and fixing the GZipStream zero-length check first.
